    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-03-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="255"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d255">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.6511/1320</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Swiss Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p>The Minister of Switzerland in charge of Italian Interests presents his
                    compliments to the Honorable the Secretary of State and, with <pb facs="0336"
                        n="324" xml:id="pg_324"/> reference to the Legation’s note of February
                        24th,<note n="36" xml:id="d255fn36">Not printed. In its reply on March 5,
                        1942, the Department informed the Swiss Legation of the result of
                        investigation of complaints as to conditions at White Sulphur Springs. Some
                        complaints were found unwarranted, some requests were met, and others were
                        referred to the Department of Justice. (701.6511/1304)</note> has the honor
                    to transmit the following communication received from the Italian Government,
                    through the intermediary of the Political Department in Bern: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The Italian Government would regret to be compelled to apply
                            restrictions similar to those adopted in regard to the personnel of the
                            Italian Embassy in the United States if the United States Government
                            should not give favorable consideration to the requests presented by
                            Ambassador Colonna, inasmuch as: <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item>The American diplomats in Rome continue to enjoy a privileged
                                    treatment as to food and clothing.</item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>The Americans are free to move about at their pleasure if
                                    escorted, with the sole restriction of not being allowed to
                                    visit public places.</item>
                                <label>3.</label>
                                <item>Children are entirely free to go wherever they wish.</item>
                                <label>4.</label>
                                <item>The purchase of books and magazines is permitted.”</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-02">March 2,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
